summary.seg: This manuscript, produced in the 17th century, is a copy of Xenophon's Anabasis. The text is a historical memoir of the participation in a Persian civil war in the 4th century BCE of a force of Greek mercenaries, one of whose commanders was the author himself, and their tortuous retreat to the Black Sea after their employer's defeat. The manuscript also contains a series of brief Latin poems on different fruits.

msItem.author: Xenophon
msItem.title: Anabasis
msItem.incipit: p. 1 Δαρείου καὶ Μαρυσάτιδος γίγνονται παῖδες δύο πρεσβύτερος μὲν Ἀρταξέρξης
msItem.explicit: p. 217 χρόνου πλῆθος τ'ἀναβάσεως καὶ καταβάσεως, ἐνιαυτὸς, τρεῖς μῆνες

msItem.title: Poems on fruit
msItem.incipit: p. 218 Primus veni ficus, primi tibi conscia lapsus
msItem.explicit: p. 218 iamque nolam linguae fructus amarus habet

support.material: Western paper, folded in octavo. Watermark: Foolscap ( c. 65 40 ) at the tail-end of the gutter.

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript is paginated with the numbers [i-ii] + 1-218 + [iii], in pencil, in Arabic numerals, recto, upper right.

collation.p: The manuscript consists of 14 quires, of which one is a ternion and the rest are quaternia.

list.item: Quire 16-2+1 f. [ii]-p. 6 The first two folios of this quire are pasted to the left cover; a separate bifolio has been inserted after them, the left-hand leaf of which is the visible left pastedown, while the right-hand leaf is the endleaf f. [i].
Quire 28+1 pp. 7-24 The last folio has been tipped to the quire.
Quire 48-1 pp. 41-54 The first folio has been cancelled, without loss of text.
Quire 148+2 pp. 199-218 The last two folios have been tipped to the quire.

supportDesc.condition: There is wear and tear to the edges of some folios, and areas of dirt.

layoutDesc.layout: pp. 1-217 A single column of 33 lines. 127 67
p. 218 A single column of 26 lines. 132 77

handNote.p: The Greek text was copied in an upright western European mixed minuscule script, in brown ink.
Punctuation used includes the lower point and lower comma.

binding.p: 17th-century limp vellum binding, with plain pastedowns. The classmark appears on the spine on patches.

accMat.p: A plain paper bifolio at each end forms a pastedown and outer endleaf. At the left-hand end, this bifolio is inserted after the the first two folios of the opening quire, which have also been pasted to the left pastedown; the third folio of the quire forms a second endleaf, f. [ii].

A printed note recording the manuscript's donation to Trinity College by James Duport has been pasted to the left pastedown: Trin. Coll. Cantab. E Libris quos Reverendus Vir Iacobus Duport, S.T.D. Decanus Petroburgensis, Et huius Collegii quondam Vicemagister, huic Bibliothecae legavit.

history.origin: The manuscript was probably copied between about 1600 and 1679, as suggested by the type of watermark and the date of death of the donor.
history.acquisition: Given to Trinity College by the classical scholar James Duport (1606-1679) Duport, James, 1606-1679 , Dean of Peterborough, Master of Magdalene College and former Vice-Master of Trinity, as indicated by the printed note on the left pastedown.
